<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Lorenz_cipher&action=edit&section=1.php.html" title="Edit section: The Vernam cipher">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="The_Vernam_cipher">The Vernam cipher</span></h2>
<div class="rellink relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <a href="Gilbert_Vernam" title="Gilbert Vernam">Gilbert Vernam</a></div>
<p><a href="Gilbert_Vernam" title="Gilbert Vernam">Gilbert Vernam</a> was an <a href="AT&T_Corporation" title="AT&amp;T Corporation">AT&amp;T</a> <a href="Bell_Labs" title="Bell Labs">Bell Labs</a> research engineer who, in 1917, invented a cipher system that used the <a href="Boolean_algebra_(logic)" title="Boolean algebra (logic)" class="mw-redirect">Boolean</a> <a href="Exclusive_or" title="Exclusive or">"exclusive or" (XOR)</a> function, symbolised by ‚äï.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup> This is represented by the following "<a href="Truth_table" title="Truth table">truth table</a>", where 1 represents "true" and 0 represents "false".</p>
<table class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto">
<tr bgcolor="#DDEEFF" align="center">
<td colspan="2"><b>INPUT</b></td>
<td><b>OUTPUT</b></td>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor="#DDEEFF" align="center">
<td><i><b>A</b></i></td>
<td><i><b>B</b></i></td>
<td><b><i>A</i> ‚äï<i>B</i></b></td>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor="#DDFFDD" align="center">
<td><b>0</b></td>
<td><b>0</b></td>
<td><b>0</b></td>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor="#DDFFDD" align="center">
<td><b>0</b></td>
<td><b>1</b></td>
<td><b>1</b></td>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor="#DDFFDD" align="center">
<td><b>1</b></td>
<td><b>0</b></td>
<td><b>1</b></td>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor="#DDFFDD" align="center">
<td><b>1</b></td>
<td><b>1</b></td>
<td><b>0</b></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>Other names for this function are: Not equal (NEQ), <a href="Modular_arithmetic" title="Modular arithmetic">modulo</a> 2 addition (without 'carry') and modulo 2 subtraction (without 'borrow').</p>
<p>Vernam's cipher is a <a href="Symmetric-key_algorithm" title="Symmetric-key algorithm">Symmetric-key algorithm</a>, i.e. the same <a href="Key_(cryptography)" title="Key (cryptography)">key</a> is used both to encipher <a href="Plaintext" title="Plaintext">plaintext</a> to produce the <a href="Ciphertext" title="Ciphertext">ciphertext</a> and to decipher ciphertext to yield the original plaintext:</p>
<dl>
<dd>
<dl>
<dd>
<dl>
<dd>
<dl>
<dd>Plaintext ‚äï Key = Ciphertext</dd>
</dl>
</dd>
</dl>
</dd>
</dl>
</dd>
</dl>
<p>and:</p>
<dl>
<dd>
<dl>
<dd>
<dl>
<dd>
<dl>
<dd>Ciphertext ‚äï Key = Plaintext</dd>
</dl>
</dd>
</dl>
</dd>
</dl>
</dd>
</dl>
<p>This produces the essential reciprocity that allows the same machine with the same settings to be used for both enciphering and deciphering.</p>
<p>Vernam's idea was to use conventional telegraphy practice with a paper tape of the plaintext combined with a paper tape of the key. Each key tape would have been unique (a one-time tape), but generating and distributing such tapes presented considerable practical difficulties. In the 1920s four men in different countries invented rotor cipher machines to produce a key stream to act instead of a tape.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup> The 1940 Lorenz SZ40/42 was one of these.<sup id="cite_ref-GRoT11B10_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GRoT11B10-8"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Lorenz_cipher&action=edit&section=2.php.html" title="Edit section: Structure">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Structure">Structure</span></h2>
<p>The logical functioning of the Tunny system was worked out well before the Bletchley Park cryptanalysts saw one of the machines‚Äîwhich only happened in 1945, shortly before the allied victory in Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-Sale_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Sale-9"><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:342px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:SZ42-6-wheels-lightened.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/SZ42-6-wheels-lightened.jpg/340px-SZ42-6-wheels-lightened.jpg" width="340" height="255" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/SZ42-6-wheels-lightened.jpg/510px-SZ42-6-wheels-lightened.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/SZ42-6-wheels-lightened.jpg/680px-SZ42-6-wheels-lightened.jpg 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:SZ42-6-wheels-lightened.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf7/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The Lorenz SZ machines had 12 wheels each with a different number of cams (or "pins").
